Step 1: Raw Read Quality Control
Tool Used
FastQC / Falco
Purpose of the Step
The first step was checking the quality of the raw sequencing reads before starting genome assembly. FastQC and Falco were used to assess the sequencing data and identify any issues that could affect subsequent analysis.
The programs checked:
Sequence quality
GC content
Adapter contamination
Read length
Duplicate sequences
Unknown bases called “N.”
Why its done
Raw sequencing reads usually contain low quality sections and leftover adapter sequences. Too many unknown bases mean the sequencing machine could not tell which DNA base belonged there.
This step was important because poor quality reads can cause problems during:
Genome assembly
Gene annotation
Species identification
Resistance analysis
The quality reports indicated that the reads were sufficient to proceed after trimming and cleaning.

Step 2: Read Trimming and Filtering
Tool Used
fastp
Purpose of the Step
After quality control, Fastp was used to clean the sequencing reads. This tool was removed:
Low quality bases
Adapter sequences
Short reads
Sequencing errors
Data Obtained
One sample started with about:
18.29 million reads
After filtering:
About 17.56 million reads remained
Why its being done
This showed that bad quality reads and contaminants were successfully removed while keeping most of the data.
Cleaning the reads improved:
Genome assembly accuracy
Read reliability
Overall analysis quality
This step helped make the downstream analysis more accurate and easier to interpret.

Step 3: Genome Assembly
Tool Used
SPAdes Genome Assembler
Purpose of the Step
SPAdes was used to assemble the cleaned sequencing reads into longer DNA pieces called contigs. The program searched for overlapping sections between reads and joined them to reconstruct the bacterial genome.
Results Obtained
The final assembly produced:
Around 35 contigs
Genome size between 2.79 and 2.89 Mb
GC content around 32.7%
Notes and Interpretation
These values closely matched known Staphylococcus aureus genomes.
The lower number of contigs suggested that most of the genome was successfully reconstructed. Even though the genome was not completely closed into one chromosome, the assembly was complete enough for further analysis.
This step changed the raw sequencing reads into a usable bacterial genome.

Step 4: Assembly Quality Evaluation
Tool Used
QUAST
Purpose of the Step
QUAST was used to check the quality of the assembled genome. The program looked at:
Genome size
Number of contigs
GC content
Assembly fragmentation
Coverage information
Why its being done
The assembly statistics matched what is normally expected for Staphylococcus aureus.
The genome size and GC content appeared biologically reasonable, and the assembly quality was sufficient to proceed with annotation and genome analysis.
This step was important because poor assemblies can lead to:
Missing genes
Incorrect annotations
False resistance predictions
Weak comparative genomics results

Step 5: Genome Annotation
Tool Used
Prokka
Purpose of the Step
Prokka was used to identify genes and functional regions within the assembled genome.
The annotation process identified:
Coding genes
Ribosomal RNA genes
Transfer RNA genes
Hypothetical proteins
Other functional regions
Why its being done
This step converted the DNA sequence into interpretable biological information.
Many genes related to bacterial survival and metabolism were identified throughout the genome. A large number of hypothetical proteins were also found. These are predicted genes whose functions are not yet fully understood.
Annotation was important because it allowed later identification of:
Resistance genes
Survival pathways
Iron uptake systems
Virulence related genes

Step 6: Species Identification and Comparative Genomics
Tools Used
BLAST
OrthoANI Calculator
Purpose of the Step
BLAST and ANI analysis were used to compare the assembled genome against known bacterial genomes to confirm the species identity.
ANI Results
Comparison 1
ANI value: 97.61%
Genome coverage: about 64 to 66%
Comparison 2
ANI value: 98.81%
Genome coverage: about 67%
Comparison 3
ANI value: 99.00%
Genome coverage: about 60 to 62%
Why its being done
ANI values above 95 percent usually mean two bacteria belong to the same species.
All three ANI comparisons were above 95 percent, strongly confirming that the isolate was Staphylococcus aureus.
The highest ANI value, 99 percent, indicated a very close relationship with known Staphylococcus aureus reference genomes.
The small differences in genome coverage suggested that the isolate may still contain some strain level differences.

Step 7: CRISPR Analysis
Tool Used
CRISPRCasFinder
Purpose of the Step
CRISPRCasFinder was used to search the genome for:
CRISPR arrays
Spacer sequences
Cas proteins
Defense related regions
Results Obtained from this
Several CRISPR associated regions and evidence scores were identified across the genome.
Notes and Interpretation
CRISPR systems work like a bacterial immune system. They help bacteria protect themselves from:
Viruses
Foreign DNA
Plasmids
The presence of these regions suggested that the Staphylococcus aureus isolate may have defense systems against outside genetic material.

Step 8: Secondary Metabolite Analysis
Tool Used
AntiSMASH
Purpose of the Step
AntiSMASH was used to identify biosynthetic gene clusters involved in secondary metabolite production.
These pathways are connected to:
Iron uptake
Survival
Communication
Environmental adaptation
Possible pathogenicity
Results Obtained
Several important clusters were identified, including:
Staphyloferrin A
Staphyloferrin B
Aureusimine A
Aureusimine B
Staphopine related pathways
NRPS related regions
Terpene regions
Cyclic lactone autoinducer pathways
Why did it all happened
The staphyloferrin clusters were important because they help Staphylococcus aureus collect iron from the environment. Iron is very important for bacterial growth, especially during infection, where iron is limited.
The staphopine pathways suggested advanced metal uptake systems that may improve bacterial survival under stressful conditions.
The NRPS and aureusimine pathways may help with:
Cell communication
Stress response
Bacterial survival
Possible virulence
The cyclic lactone autoinducer regions may also help bacteria communicate with each other through quorum sensing.

Step 9: Antimicrobial Resistance Analysis
Tool Used
ResFinder
Purpose of the Step
ResFinder was used to search the genome for antimicrobial resistance genes.
Notes and Interpretation
Resistance related regions were identified within the Staphylococcus aureus genome. These findings suggested that the isolate may contain genes connected to antibiotic resistance or tolerance.
Resistance genes are important because they may:
Make antibiotics less effective
Help bacteria survive treatment
Increase public health concerns
This step added important clinical information to the genome analysis.
